  {
   "ms": 119553,
   "dir": "recv",
   "frame": {
    "type": "message",
    "role": "assistant",
    "text": "Here's the sequence laid out on the board, from the power connector to the CPU module. Let me walk you through it in order — it's exactly the path the current takes when you press power.\n\n## The conductor: U18 (the LPC)\nFirst things first, remember **U18** (highlighted in orange). It's a small ARM Cortex-⟨?M0⟩ microcontroller (NXP LPC11U24). It doesn't \"compute\" anything useful for you — its only job is to **bring the rails up in the right order**, through its GPIOs. Until it wakes up (or if it has a dead pin), **no main rail comes up**. That's key reason #1 for a \"won't start\".\n\n## The rails coming up, phase by phase\n\n**Phase 0 — Permanent standby (always-on)**\nAs soon as 24 V is plugged in: the battery + `LPC_VCC` + the RTC are powered permanently. The LPC is powered and waiting for the power-on command.\n\n**Phase 1 — VIN stage (input + charging)**\n24 V enters through fuse **F1** (highlighted in red — also suspect #1 for a dead board), passes the inrush limiter **Q3**, then reaches the charger/booster **U2** which generates the `VIN` rail. The `VIN / LPC_VCC / VOUT / 5V_OUT / INTVCC` rails stabilize.\n\n**Phase 2 — Main rails (the LPC opens the valves)**\nVIN stable → the LPC asserts two enable signals:\n- `5V_PWR_EN` → **U7** outputs **+5V**\n- `3V3_PWR_EN` → **U12** outputs **+3V3**\n\n**Phase 3 — SoC core rails**\nThe LPC continues (these converters are fed from +5V, so necessarily after):\n- `1V5_PWR_EN` → **U19** outputs **+1V5**\n- `1V2_PWR_EN` → **U13** outputs **+1V2**\n\n**Phase 4 — AUX + USB + the CPU module**\n`AUX_PWR_EN` → **U27** (auxiliary 3V3 switch), `USB_PWR_EN` → the USB supply, and the i.MX8M module plugged into connector **U1** finally gets all its voltages and starts to boot.\n\n**Phases 5-6 — On demand**\nOnce the SoC is alive, it requests PCIe itself, then the backlight, then the USB / HDMI / audio hub.\n\n## What to remember for your symptom\nThis board's golden rule: **F1 → U2 → U18 (LPC) → U7/U12 → the rest**. If it \"won't start, no power at all\", you walk this chain in order — you don't jump straight to the SoC. The two most common starting points are **F1** (open fuse, board completely dead) and **U18** (LPC no longer sequencing).\n\nWant to tackle the \"no power\" diagnostic now? If so, tell me: is there **a LED lighting up somewhere**, and do you measure **24 V at the input**? That tells us right away whether we're stuck before or after F1."
   }
